    {
      "id": 16,
      "type": "Note",
      "pos": [
        -4.53915432246539,
        -638.8553176876957
      ],
      "size": [
        2900,
        380
      ],
      "flags": {},
      "order": 1,
      "mode": 0,
      "inputs": [],
      "outputs": [],
      "properties": {
        "text": ""
      },
      "widgets_values": [
        "ATLAS COMPLETE DMP PIPELINE — the full matte-painting story in one graph (sky dome + depth-layered clean plates + disocclusion fill + true depth-shadow occlusion)\n\nThis is the capstone example tying together the whole Atlas Camera inpaint/projection system:\n\n1. SKY: a real segmentation (placeholder SolidMask here — swap for ComfyUI-RMBG's SAM3 Segmentation prompted 'sky') separates the sky onto AtlasSkyDomeLayer's flat far card, clean-plated and projected independently of noisy monocular sky depth.\n2. DEPTH LAYERS: AtlasDepthLayerMask splits the solved photo into metric bands; its occlusion_mask drives an external inpaint (placeholder: original photo wired directly — swap for INPAINT_ExpandMask -> INPAINT_InpaintWithModel per INSTALL.md) to build each band's clean plate; AtlasCleanPlateLayer projects each plate onto its own band-clipped relief mesh.\n3. DISOCCLUSION FILL (fill_occluded=True, new): the band clip normally leaves a hole in the background mesh exactly where the foreground occluder stood — the inpainted plate had pixels there but no geometry. fill_occluded diffusion-fills the occluder footprint's depth from the surrounding background, so orbiting now reveals INPAINTED CONTENT ON REAL GEOMETRY instead of a hole. n_filled_cells is recorded in the layer's metadata; AtlasDepthLayerMask's matching fill_occluded keeps its pre-inpaint hole_mask in lockstep.\n4. DEPTH-SHADOW OCCLUSION (occlusion_mode=depth_shadow, new): AtlasOcclusionMask now detects true MPTK-style self-occlusion — surfaces hidden behind NEARER geometry from the primary's view — by treating the primary camera as a light and its own AtlasDepthMap as the shadow map (no render pass, pure numpy). Wire primary_depth from the same shared AtlasDepthMap. The bottom-left corner demos it; its target_image placeholder is the original photo — swap for a real Qwen Multiple-Angles novel view, then feed the composited result into AtlasAddPatchView per the multi-angle patch pipeline.\n\nRun it, open the Atlas Viewport, hit Project, then orbit/dolly: sky stays clean on its card, depth layers separate in parallax, and the previously-black disocclusion hole behind the foreground now shows the (placeholder) plate on synthesized geometry.\n\nSee CLAUDE.md's 'Inpaint layers', 'Multi-angle patch projection', and 'Relief mesh tearing' key design rules."
      ],
      "color": "#432",
      "bgcolor": "#653"
    },
